4429,'',"Ghost middleware is wrong\n# Ghost middleware is wrong\r\n## The problem\r\nBefore I begin, let me present the middleware displayed in the wiki\r\n\r\n```\r\nvar ghost = require('ghost'),\r\n    express = require('express'),\r\n    parentApp = express();\r\n\r\nghost().then(function (ghostServer) {\r\n    parentApp.use(ghostServer.config.paths.subdir, ghostServer.rootApp);\r\n\r\n    ghostServer.start(parentApp);\r\n});\r\n```\r\nIn this snippet, there are two major problems and a minor inconvenience\r\n1. The whole parent application has to wait around for the child to start up\r\n2. The parent gets started **by** the child.\r\n3. (minor) It doesn't really follow the footprint of most other Express middleware\r\n\r\n### 1. Parent has to wait\r\nThis model defeats the whole point of Ghost-as-middleware.\r\nThe primary use case for middleware is to integrate Ghost into a larger body of code (like a corperate website w/ blog). It must therefore be as unobtrusive as possible.\r\nIf the parent's timing is dictated by the startup process of the child, it becomes awkward instead of beautiful. The clean ideas of express middleware are gone.\r\n\r\n### 2. Child starts parent\r\nThis is a breach of seperation concerns. Why is Ghost calling .listen() on the parent app? The parent app is none of Ghost's business.\r\n\r\n## The Ideal\r\nThe way I imagine a proper parent-ghost middleware relationship\r\n\r\n```\r\nvar express = require( 'express' ) \r\nvar ghost = require( 'ghost' )\r\nvar parent = express()\r\n\r\nparent.use( '/store', require( 'some-store-middleware' ) )\r\nparent.use( '/games', require( 'some-games-sub-site' ) )\r\n//... etc etc\r\n\r\n// Ghost sets up to handle requests given to it, and **nothing more**\r\nparent.use( '/blog', ghost(options) )\r\n\r\n// ...more things, set up, complicated calculations of the meaning of life, etc\r\n\r\n//THEN the parent starts up on its own time\r\nparent.listen( parent.get( 'port' ) )\r\n```\r\n# Possible solution\r\nI understand that Ghost is a bit tricky to `require`, since that only provides a promise of future functionality.\r\n\r\nThe way I tackled this back when I was trying to make a push for Ghost middleware is as follows.\r\n*Note: the exact file references might be a bit out of date as there have been over 700 commits since this was written*\r\n\r\n```\r\n// /core/middleware.js\r\nvar ghost = require('./index'),\r\n    errors = require('./server/errors');\r\n\r\nfunction ghostMiddleware(options) {\r\n    var app = false,\r\n        requestBuffer = [];\r\n\r\n    ghost(options).then(function (blog) {\r\n        app = blog.app;\r\n        while (requestBuffer.length) {\r\n            app.apply(app, requestBuffer.pop());\r\n        }\r\n    }).catch(function (err) {\r\n        errors.logErrorAndExit(err, err.context, err.help);\r\n    });\r\n\r\n    return function (req, res) {\r\n        if (app === false) {\r\n            requestBuffer.unshift([req, res]);\r\n        } else {\r\n            app(req, res);\r\n        }\r\n    };\r\n}\r\n\r\nmodule.exports = ghostMiddleware;\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis solution provides express with immediately useful, valid middleware.\r\nIn the background, the middleware is caching all incoming requests while it waits for Ghost to be prepared. Once this happens, the middleware routes the backlog of requests in through the application.\r\n\r\nThis is only one potential solution. All I know is that the current implimentation does not sit well with me. Thoughts and critisisms more than welcome."
