4389,'','Re-add Node-Sass Dependency\nReferences #4355 and #4372\r\n\r\nThere was an issue where Libsass/node-sass would strip media queries (https://github.com/sass/libsass/issues/566 & https://github.com/sass/node-sass/issues/487). It is fixed now, but the dependencies in grunt-sass have not yet been updated.\r\n\r\nThis PR requires a never version of node-sass which fixes the issue.'
4386,'','Clicking "Meta Data" adds a hash to the url\nIssue Summary\r\n-----------------------------------\r\n\r\nClicking on the Meta Data button on the post-settings-menu appends a hash to the url, so that `/editor/1/` becomes `/editor/1/#`.\r\n\r\nThis is ugly and sad. We do our best to never have `#` appear in the url; it would seem we left behind an `href="#"` somewhere though.\r\n\r\nReproduction Steps\r\n----------------------------------\r\n\r\n1. Edit a post\r\n2. Click the cog (open the PSM)\r\n3. Click on Meta Data\r\n\r\nSpecs\r\n-----------------\r\n\r\n- Chrome 38\r\n- MacOSx10\r\n- Latest master, 8d96cb2f6793d231f805e2ed5fb328cdde8be91f'
4385,'','Save meta title and meta desc on post save\nCloses #4369\r\nI may also have gotten carried away refactoring the editor-base-route mixin.\r\n- Renamed `editor-route-base` -> `editor-base-route` to bring it in alignment with the view and controller mixins\r\n- Consolidated editor route code into editor-base-route\r\n- Removed `serialize` from EditorEditRoute, as it reimplemented the ember default\r\n\r\n![save meta](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1207005/4894781/f360bd5c-63d9-11e4-9f5b-9085fdeb51f4.gif)\r\n'
4384,'','fix bug in which `logError` could not resolve an err without `message`\nfixed #4381\r\n - if an error object has no property `message`, an new error could been produced'
4383,'','theme:content should allow for parsing paragraphs\ncontent currently allows you to set the number of words or characters as a blogroll preview, but I believe allowing users to set full paragraphs would be beneficial as well.\r\n\r\n```xml\r\n<div class="post-content">\r\n    {{content paragraphs="1"}}\r\n</div>\r\n```'
4381,'',"Bug: error without message could make a new error\nfile: [core/server/errors/index.js](https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/blob/master/core/server/errors/index.js)\r\nLine: 110\r\n```\r\nerr = _.isString(err) ? err : (_.isObject(err) ? err.message : 'An unknown error occurred.');\r\nif (err.indexOf('SQLITE_READONLY') !== -1) {\r\n```\r\nIf `err` is like this:\r\n ```\r\n{\r\ncode: 401, error: 'expired token' \r\n}\r\n```\r\nthen an new error `ERROR: Cannot call method 'indexOf' of undefined ` will be thrown."
4380,'','Update Sass Grunt task output style\nNo issue\r\n\r\nA recent update to NodeSass changed the keyword for output style from `style` to `outputStyle`.\r\nThis updates that, thus making the minfied CSS, actually minfied.'
4378,'',"[bug] Tags are suffixing, rather than using the original\nI've seen this happen twice now, and will try to come up with reliable repro steps.\r\n\r\nI have a tag on my blog, [Sinks Canyon](http://blog.novaugust.net/tag/sinks-canyon). I was surprised when one of my latest posts about the canyon wasn't in that list, but when I looked at my post, it does have the tag. However, its tag was given the slug `sinks-canyon-2`, so it kind of [orphaned itself](blog.novaugust.net/tag/sinks-canyon-2).\r\n\r\nEven though it's the same tag, it created a new tag, when it should have just recognized that i was using the same tag.\r\n\r\nAt a guess, this may be because i manually typed out the tag, rather than using the tag-suggestion tool?\r\n\r\n-----------------\r\n\r\n*Update*: I fixed my blog's tags, not thinking about the fact that I'd linked it from this issue. `sinks-canyon-2` doesn't have any posts anymore, but it looks like HW is right about there being a trimming issue"
4377,'','emacs save files loaded with partials in theme?\nGhost 0.5.3\r\nNode 10.33\r\nUbuntu 14.04\r\nProxying via Apache\r\n\r\nI\'m using the "Willsong" theme, and needed to make some changes to the header and post partials in order to change navigation and enable disqus.  However, despite multiple restarts, I couldn\'t get any of my edits to the themes to show.  I even tried switching away from the theme, renaming it, and switching to the renamed theme.  In the course of testing, I probably restarted node 15 times and even restarted Apache twice and closed and reloaded my browser for good measure.\r\n\r\nSo then I tried deleting the old versions of the partials stored as emacs save files (e.g. "menu.hds~"), and restarting.  This suddenly allowed my edits to show up.  The only conclusion I can come to is that ".hds~" files get loaded as if they were hds files. Even if this isn\'t something you can/want to fix, there should be a warning to users somewhere in the docs.'
