4233,'',"Multiple pages in a post\nThe feature I'm requesting is something like ArsTechnica's [multiple-page articles](http://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2014/08/kde-plasma-5-for-those-linux-users-undecided-on-the-kernels-future/). [Here is a quick mockup](https://moqups.com/clayton.sean@gmail.com/50OQwWcD/) I made for what the admin UI would look like for this.\r\n\r\nI feel like extremely long articles need to be broken down into multiple pages. It opens up opportunities for better experiences with articles such as long-winded reviews, thoughts, etc because users won't have to scroll endlessly to get from one idea/section to another.\r\n\r\nFor example, [this article](http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/10/os-x-10-9/) would be (I'm being honest here) rather painful with just one long article. I'm not sure having multiple articles/posts would solve this dilemma, either.\r\n\r\nI'm sure there are many other writers out there who write essays/research papers/thought pieces that end up taking a lot of words/ideas to finish, and having multiple pages would alleviate the worry of doing one of those."
4232,'','Error deleting content when number of posts > 999 and database is sqlite3\nSqlite3 has a limit of 999 bound parameters, so if a collection of models is greater than 999 and eager fetching of relations is attempted (`withRelated`) the query will fail:\r\n\r\n![screen shot 2014-10-02 at 3 54 09 pm](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/214142/4498642/1e8804b4-4a7a-11e4-8de3-469eb86b9f66.png)\r\n\r\nWhat probably needs to happen is `findAll` in `core/server/models/posts.js` needs to be adjusted to not eagerly fetch relations by default but instead just take `options.include` and assign it to `options.withRelated`.'
4231,'cobbspur','Create theme image helpers with absolute attributes\nCurrently we use handlebars to output raw data from:\r\n\r\n* `{{image}}`\r\n* `{{author.image}}`\r\n\r\nThese output relative url paths to the image files. It would be helpful if these were turned into helpers supporting an absolute value, eg.\r\n\r\n* `{{image absolute="true"}}`\r\n* `{{author.image absolute="true"}}`\r\n\r\nWith output including `@blog.url` prepended to the image path.\r\n\r\nPrimary use-case: For valid output in meta tags, eg. in #3900 '
