4039,'',"Add option to specify reporter and output file via grunt.\nFixes #4038.\r\n- This allows continuous integration platforms like Jenkins to retrieve\r\n  and parse tests results easily.\r\n- It uses tap-file as a Mocha reporter to output unit tests results to a\r\n  file. A FILE_TAP environment variable needs to be set in order to\r\n  specify the file path where the tests results will be stored.\r\n- It uses casperjs' --xunit command line switch to output functional\r\n  tests results to a file.\r\n- phantomjs and casperjs are added to devDependencies so that the\r\n  continuous integration platform doesn't have to setup these\r\n  dependencies itself.\r\n- Currently, phantomjs dependency is set to version 1.9.1-7 because\r\n  that's the only version working on SmartOS, and I need it to work on\r\n  SmartOS. However, if that's an issue, I can work around that on my\r\n  side.\r\n- Node engine has been set to >= 0.10.0 so that Ghost can be tested\r\n  against Node 0.11.x-pre versions (and later)."
4038,'','Output tests results to files to allow for easy retrieval and parsing when tests are run on continuous integration platforms\nI\'m currently working on setting up a Jenkins job that tests Ghost against Node.js\' v0.12 branch (which contains the code for the upcoming 0.12 stable version). While doing so, I wanted to be able to run all tests (`npm test`) and parse the results so that I could examine tests failures easily.\r\n\r\nWith the current code base, I don\'t see how I can achieve that without changing Ghost\'s code. The tests results are outputted to standard error or output, and it makes parsing tests results difficult.\r\n\r\nHaving a separate npm script like "test-ci" that outputs tests results to files would be very helpful.'
