3979,'','[Discussion] Theme package.json: Declare compatible Ghost version\nI am on a quest to reduce the confusion around Ghost themes and whether they are compatible with a specific version of Ghost, as well as improve the rate at which themes get updated when we add or remove features. 9 months after we originally introduced the required `{{asset}}` helper, and 6 months after `{{pageUrl}}` was deprecated and `package.json` added, I still see many themes which haven\'t updated for one of these changes.\r\n\r\nOne part of this is very definitely our lack of communication. Although I always blog about changes, there has never been a good resource. Today I\'ve done a first pass of a [theme API change log](http://docs.ghost.org/themes/changelog/) which I hope to see expand into a resource which details every change, the impact, how to upgrade your theme etc.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, it is time to start requiring that a theme declare which version of Ghost it is compatible with in the package.json file.\r\n\r\nI am not 100% certain whether this is a correct use-case for `peerDependences`, or  whether we should do something like:\r\n\r\n```\r\n{\r\n  "name": "Casper",\r\n  "version": "1.0.1"\r\n  "ghost": {\r\n     "version": "0.5.0"\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nWe already use the Ghost key for `ghost.permissions` for apps, so it may make sense to keep all of our custom Ghost related keys under a single `ghost` key? \r\n\r\nWhichever we choose, the result should be a Ghost startup warning around themes that are incompatible. A theme should be deemed *incompatible* if:\r\n\r\n- it does not have a package.json\r\n- it has a package.json but no Ghost version specified\r\n- it has a specified Ghost version which is lower than the current Ghost version (according to semver)\r\n\r\nNote: At the same time as we introduce this, I also want to introduce the requirement that a theme\'s `package.json` specifies the `author` key (name, version and author are required to be a valid package.json file according to npm). There should be warnings output by Ghost if `name`, `version`, `author` or whatever we pick for declaring the Ghost version is missing.\r\n\r\nOnce we\'ve shipped this change, and done a bit of extra communication to theme developers around these changes, there are two further steps I think we ought to take (in subsequent releases, so that the move towards requiring this is gradual but very clear).\r\n\r\nFirst, we\'ll add a top notification to any blog whose active theme is *incompatible*. This won\'t affect anything, but will encourage blog owners to nag their respective theme developers. \r\n\r\nSecond, we\'ll make it so that it is not possible to activate an *incompatible* theme. Ghost will still start if the theme is already activated, but any attempt to choose a theme which is incompatible from the dropdown should fail with a sensible notification.\r\n\r\nSummary of tasks:\r\n\r\n- [ ] decide on a format for the Ghost version, peerDep or ghost.version\r\n- [ ] make Ghost output startup warnings if it is missing\r\n- [ ] make Ghost output startup warnings if `author` is missing\r\n- [ ] **bonus** create a way to determine if the currently active theme is *incompatible* perhaps via a theme API endpoint'
