2978,'',"[WIP] Functional tests for Ember\nThought I'd PR this to demonstrate that it is coming along.\r\n\r\nMain things outstanding:\r\n- The ember editor doesn't work under test conditions at present\r\n- Need to finish converting the settings tests\r\n\r\nI'm really not sure what's happening with the Editor. When run under the casper tests the `bind` method is undefined on [this line](https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/blob/master/core/client/components/gh-codemirror.js#L40) and [this line](https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/blob/master/core/client/components/gh-codemirror.js#L8) causing an error which means the editor doesn't initialise.\r\n\r\nIf I comment out those lines it sort of works but obviously the functionality they pertain to breaks. I'm not sure what's happening to cause bind to be undefined, I've tried adding a massive delay (weird casper test issues are usually timing errors), but that didn't help. I'm wondering if the libraries are loading in the wrong order or something. Have just done a google search (I was working without the internet) and found [this](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/22666866/casperjs-not-working-with-javascript-app-page) which I'll investigate further tomorrow.\r\n\r\n**Update:** Just to clarify what happened in this PR as there are a number of comments - bind, and a number of other modern javascript functions are not supported by Phantom.js because [reasons](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!msg/phantomjs/r0hPOmnCUpc/uxusqsl2LNoJ). Casper.js therefore also doesn't support those methods. Casper.js ships with a bind polyfil, but it only works inside of [casper itself](Bind polyfill doesn't work when testing Ember.js apps #953). I attempted to use `clientScripts` to inject the polyfil into the admin, but it happens too late, and the error has already happened before it is finished.\r\n\r\nTherefore we're left with 2 choices, 1 replace bind in the real code (which I did with lodash) or inject some polyfil manually into the code when running in the test environment. The latter is possibly a better long term solution, but I opted for lodash because it took 30seconds and time is of the essence, but raised #3010 to track this possible improvement."
