2699,'',"[Ember.js] Ember Model vs Ember Data vs ???\n[placeholder for continuing the discussion from today's meeting]\r\n\r\nHere's the link to the discussion: http://107.20.237.151:8081/logs/%23ghost/20140506#pm52129\r\n\r\nEssentially, we are trying to decide what the future of the data layer in the Ghost admin looks like. Right now we are using $.ajax, but it feels like we're having to do a lot of work ourselves that would be done for us by other solutions.\r\n\r\nSpecifically we're looking at [Ember Model](https://github.com/ebryn/ember-model), [Ember Data](http://emberjs.com/api/data/) and [Orbit.js](https://github.com/orbitjs/orbit.js/tree/master) as potential solutions - or should we just stick with $.ajax for now?\r\n\r\n**Note:** The outcome from this discussion should be a clear plan on how we are going to deal with models/data documented on https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/wiki/Ember-Admin-UI"
2698,'','Admin Area Access Facing Externally\nI am just starting out with Ghost to create a blog relating to Internet Security. The issue I would like to raise is the fact that the admin log in is an externally facing page. I realize that this is part of what makes Ghost so portable, being able to sign in and blog on the go, but for those of us who wish to lock down their blog a little better I would like to propose that it be possible for blog owners to set up some sort of IP whitelisting for administrative access. I am currently using the hosting services of Ghost (on a 30 day trial) and I see nowhere where I can apply this sort of filtering. This is probably left to a user to create if they host it on their own domain currently, but I would feel a little safer blogging with the hosting services of Ghost if this were possible. That way I could whitelist  my home IP and only be able to access the administrative panel from there. Please inform me if this is already planned (though I did check the roadmap) or if this is already being implemented and I simply have not found it. Thank you.'
2697,'','Introduce utility functions to ease API handling\nInternal handling of the API is becoming a bit more complex and uglier than originally thought. We have lots of places now where we only need to access the first element or even a specific key of the first element of an API response. One example is https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/blob/master/core/server/api/users.js#L54. In addition to having to access the first element we always need to check whether the correct elements were provided to the API (https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/blob/master/core/server/api/users.js#L10-L15) - this can be unified to work for all entities.\r\n\r\nWe had a quick discussion about this in IRC: http://107.20.237.151:8081/logs/%23ghost/20140506#pm32954\r\n\r\nThis can happen as part of the Ember work as it will not touch API responses, just clean up certain parts of the internal API handling.\r\n\r\nAlso: Dibs.'
