2622,'',"Proposal: Use JSDoc Code Documentation\nI would really love for Ghost to switch to JSDoc and start documenting all functions and variables used throughout the project.  Right now Ghost only has a scattering of code documented, making for a code base that relies on the reader to interpret all code without any help from comments and docs from the developers that implemented the code that currently exists.\r\n\r\nIn using JSDoc's it should really help make clear what arguments a function expects to receive, making for easier reading for new developers, and also acting as a way to self-validate code that is being written.  Because JavaScript is loosely typed, it's impossible to know what types of objects a function expects without either a) knowing the code base, b) logging what variables are passed into the function.\r\n\r\nCode that is annotated and documented with the JSDoc format can have documentation dynamically generated.  There are already a couple of tools available that do this:\r\n\r\n* [JSDoc itself](https://github.com/jsdoc3/jsdoc).  Some examples of generated documentation: [jaguarjs-jsdoc](http://davidshimjs.github.io/jaguarjs/doc), [docstra](http://terryweiss.github.io/docstrap/themes/spacelab/).\r\n* [dgeni](https://github.com/angular/dgeni).  Used to generate the entire [AngularJS documentation page](https://docs.angularjs.org/api).\r\n\r\nFor an example of what a fully fleshed out file with documentation looks like have a look at [Ember's Component.js file](https://github.com/emberjs/ember.js/blob/master/packages_es6/ember-views/lib/views/component.js).  I'm not sure what Ember uses to generate their documentation, or what format they use, but that could be a good solution as well.\r\n\r\nI know we used groc in the past, which uses literate programming to document itself.  I do not have that much experience with literate programming but from what I've seen of it, and from what I've seen of Ghost's codebase, it would seem that JSDoc style documentation would be of greater help to the code base and to new developers.  Additionally the ecosystem around JSDoc style documentation is stronger, with many more tools available to allow us to get moving at a faster speed.\r\n\r\nI feel like getting Ghost's code base documented will really help both existing and new devs, as well as make the code itself more robust.  Hopefully this can lead to some productive discussion.  "
