2447,'','Cache headers on Azure\nHey,\r\n\r\nI have my blog up and running on *Azure* and it\'s working quite well. I\'ve been running some speed tests today though and noticed that the default headers that Ghost uses seems a bit **unoptimized**. I\'m unsure if this is only on *Azure* or if I\'m missing something obvious. Here\'s the headers I\'m getting:\r\n\r\n| Header | Value |\r\n|-----------|---------|\r\n| Date | Wed, 19 Mar 2014 12:09:43 GMT |\r\n| Content-Encoding | gzip |\r\n| Last-Modified | Wed, 19 Mar 2014 09:30:40 GMT |\r\n| Server | Microsoft-IIS/8.0 |\r\n| X-Powered-By | Express ASP.NET |\r\n| ETag | "19761-1395221440000" |\r\n| Vary | Accept-Encoding |\r\n| Content-Type | text/css; charset=UTF-8 |\r\n| Cache-Control | public, max-age=3600 |\r\n| Accept-Ranges | bytes |\r\n| Content-Length | 5619 |\r\n\r\nAccording to [PageSpeed (Google)] (https://developers.google.com/speed/docs/insights/LeverageBrowserCaching) the `Expires` header should be set for a minimum of one week - and here it\'s missing all together.\r\n\r\nWould love some help or insight in how to get the headers right so caching is optimal. Cheers!\r\n'
2446,'','[Discussion][Ember.js] Components - Ember & Ghost-UI\nThere was a significant discussion around this in the public dev meeting yesterday, logs are [here](http://107.20.237.151:8081/logs/%23ghost/20140318#pm62116).\r\n\r\nEssentially, we are trying to decide where and how to draw the line between Ember components, and reusable [Ghost-UI](https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost-UI) components.\r\n\r\nTo clarify - the idea of Ghost-UI is to create a highly reusable frontend framework, very similar to [twitter bootstrap](http://getbootstrap.com/). A number of interactive items, such as notifications, popover menus, and modals are candidates for being components in Ghost-UI. By moving these items to Ghost-UI it becomes possible for us to reuse the styling and interactions across the Ghost admin, Ghost Apps, Ghost.org, the Marketplace, Documentation and any other Ghost properties, as well as allowing the community to make use of it in their own projects.\r\n\r\nThe difficulty is that Ember does not automatically play nicely with jQuery components, so we need to think about how we can make the Ember.js Ghost Admin, and Ghost-UI play nicely together:\r\n\r\n* Does it still make sense to separate out these components in this way? \r\n* Will we need Ember.js wrappers?\r\n* If so, what should they look like?\r\n* Is there another way to achieve our goals (reusability).'
2445,'',"[Translations: /zh] Complete Chinese translation of 'themes' docs\nAfter three commits, Chinese translation of 'themes' docs is finally completed. Thus Chinese document on http://docs.ghost.org will be perfect!"
2444,'',"Editor: Link shortcut is the same as Lock Screen on Chromebooks\nI want to add a hyperlink in my article. I do my editing on a Chromebook.\r\n\r\nThe editor shortcut to create a Link (Ctrl + Shift + L) is the [same shortcut used by ChromeOS to lock the screen](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/chromebook-central/dARs6rb3OZg). So when I attempt this, not only do I not get my link but I'm locked out of my desktop.\r\n\r\nMaybe we could use Ctrl + K like Gmail does?"
2443,'',"Refactor the API route tests to use supertest\nThere is a suite of API tests currently located in `/core/test/functional/api` which should probably live in `/core/test/functional/routes/api`.\r\n\r\nThese tests currently use request, which is awesome, but not as clear and concise as supertest.\r\n\r\nWe'd like to refactor them to use supertest the same as the admin and frontend route tests.\r\n\r\nNote: We also want to refactor the existing supertest tests: #2442"
2442,'','Use the ghost app object directly in route tests\nNow that #2225 is complete, we have a ghost() app object that we can use and depend on in tests.\r\n\r\nIt should be possible to refactor the supertest route tests in core/test/functional/routes to use the Ghost app instead of requiring that a server be started.\r\n\r\nThis should make our tests run faster and more reliably, without throwing random 500 errors.'
2441,'',"Posts should autosave.\nI was editing a post, closed my laptop for a day then came back to it.  When I re-opened my laptop I couldn't save the post so tried to refresh the browser, which lost me the post.  This is ridiculous behaviour for a blogging platform, let alone one built on an async backend like node."
2440,'','New Relic in 0.4.1 and some other issues...\nHello there!\r\nWhen I got my first Ghost server set up, I installed New Relic. As of 0.4.1, I heard that the core had been split into multiple parts. I was wondering: where would I put the New Relic monitoring code in without breaking my Ghost installation? I already had a forum topic about this, but the top contributor appeared to have abandoned the topic.\r\nhttps://ghost.org/forum/using-ghost/5695-where-is-the-ghost-js-file-in-0-4-1/\r\n\r\nAnother issue: I am building a website with the front page (the index) as Ghost. How could I put a PHP module in the /resources directory that works separately from the Ghost core? I was hoping to use the  ```node-php``` module from NPM.\r\n\r\nIt would be really helpful if I recieved an answer.'
