2367,'',"Fresh install on OSX error: Javascript files have not been built\nI am trying to setup Ghost locally to work on a custom theme. After acquiring the code, I ran into an issue. Steps I took (per [documentation](http://docs.ghost.org/installation/mac/)):\r\n\r\n```shell\r\n$ git clone <ghost-url> .\r\n$ git checkout 0.4.1\r\n$ npm install --production\r\n$ npm start\r\n```\r\n\r\n`npm start` failed with the following error. Please note it doesn't say how to fix the error. I had to look at the source code that generated the error to find out what to do.\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ npm start\r\n\r\n> ghost@0.4.1 start /Users/thomas/Code/ghost-ghost\r\n> node index\r\n\r\n\r\nERROR: Javascript files have not been built.\r\n\r\nPlease read the getting started instructions at:\r\nhttps://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost#getting-started-guide-for-developers\r\n\r\nError: Javascript files have not been built.\r\n    at /Users/thomas/Code/ghost-ghost/core/server/index.js:97:27\r\n    at Object.cb [as oncomplete] (fs.js:168:19)\r\nFrom previous event:\r\n    at exports.Common.then (/Users/thomas/Code/ghost-ghost/node_modules/knex/lib/common.js:61:33)\r\n    at getDatabaseVersion (/Users/thomas/Code/ghost-ghost/core/server/data/migration/index.js:41:45)\r\n    at Object.init (/Users/thomas/Code/ghost-ghost/core/server/data/migration/index.js:171:12)\r\n    at Object.module.exports.init (/Users/thomas/Code/ghost-ghost/core/server/models/index.js:15:27)\r\n    at setup (/Users/thomas/Code/ghost-ghost/core/server/index.js:129:12)\r\n    at init (/Users/thomas/Code/ghost-ghost/core/server/index.js:284:5)\r\n    at /Users/thomas/Code/ghost-ghost/core/index.js:13:9\r\n```"
2366,'',"[Proposal] Apps should use manifest.json instead of package.json\nThis issue is related to #2095\r\n\r\nCurrently the plan is for Ghost Apps to have a package.json, this file will declare various meta data about the App. Including name, description, keywords, an icon etc.\r\n\r\nThis will likely be extending in the future so the package.json also declares things like the Apps permissions, among others.\r\n\r\nHowever I think using a package.json has various issues \r\n\r\n* It has the potential to have clashing properties, since the same file will also be used by npm to install the Apps dependencies (although this can be worked-around).\r\n* To avoid clashing with npm Ghost related metadata could be nested in a Ghost object.\r\nAlthough this would work, it just seems wrong - Why is Ghost playing second fiddle to npm? especially considering the author is writing a Ghost App and not an npm module.\r\n* It will overload the package.json meaning, ending-up with a situation where package.json will be used for purposes it was not originally designed. \r\n* It semantically not meaningful - why is an App using a package file to declare meta-data about itself?\r\n\r\nI propose that all apps should instead be required to declare a manifest.json. \r\nI didn't make-up this name, its a convention used by other projects for example [Google Chrome](http://developer.chrome.com/extensions/manifest/) requires a manifest.json when writing apps/extension . This is also used by [Firefox OS](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/Apps/Build/Manifest).\r\n\r\nOptionally apps can also use package.json if the App has npm dependencies and possibly even a bower.json if the App has client-side dependencies that live on the bower registry.\r\n"
2363,'',"Text is not rendering in Chrome.\nI just installed Ghost on Openshift using their Quickstart. Chrome is not rendering the text and possibly other elements (tested in Win 8 and Win 7). Certain things will cause it to load correctly, like bringing up the developer tools. Refresh the page and the text disappears. \r\nThe elements are loading in the DOM.\r\nSomeone noticed this same issue in Safari mobile https://ghost.org/forum/using-ghost/4703-refreshing-issue-on-mobile-safari/4/, but I haven't confirmed it."
2362,'','Discuss: Standard spec for JSON REST API?\nAs @sebgie seems to be cleaning up the JSON REST API I would like to start a discussion why or why not it could make sense to use a standard spec/format for the API.\r\n\r\nThe format suggested by @sebgie in https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/issues/2347, https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/issues/2348, https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/issues/2349, https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/issues/2350 looks beautiful and straight forward to use. \r\n\r\nIn the last 1-2 years several standard formats/specs/media-types for HYPERMEDIA APIS have been developed. \r\n\r\nPRO\r\n+ Profit from clear set of rules + expertise of creators\r\n+ There are libraries/tools that can provide/consume these standards out of the box. This reduces the dependency between client and server - loose coupling!\r\n+ Clients could consume it based on a API description.\r\n\r\nCON\r\n- standards are young and still evolving\r\n\r\nSome standards:\r\n* [JSON API](http://jsonapi.org/format) - The standard format used by Ember Data! The current ghost API seems already close to this format. By @steveklabnik \r\n* [HAL](http://stateless.co/hal_specification.html)\r\n* [Collection+JSON](http://amundsen.com/media-types/collection/)\r\n* [Siren](https://github.com/kevinswiber/siren)\r\n* [Restful Objects](http://restfulobjects.org/)\r\n* [OData](http://www.odata.org/)\r\n\r\n*Edit: Added OData as suggested by @ErisDS*\r\n'
