2323,'','Combine excerpt & content so can have UI field?\nI was just thinking, given we don\'t have a "more" tag insertion function, and people often have quite different preferences on how they want to show content on their homepage & archives (i.e. length, stripping html or not), would this work?\r\n\r\nBoth the "excerpt" and "content" helpers accept "words" and "characters" as options. The difference between the two helpers is that one strips html and the other doesn\'t.\r\n\r\nSo what if instead of having the "excerpt" helper, we had "strip_html" as an option for the "content" helper?\r\n\r\nThe functions of the two helpers could then be combined into one, with the processing method and returned value depending on the "strip_html" setting, and it could be used in a theme like:\r\n\r\n{{content characters / words="100" strip_html="true / false"}}\r\n\r\n(The "strip_html" property would default to false. If "strip_html" were true and no characters / words option were set it could still default to 50 words).\r\n\r\nIf we did this, perhaps that would also lay the ground work for a UI setting to allow users to control each of these values.\r\n\r\nSo perhaps under the current "Posts per page" setting there could also be something like:\r\n\r\n* _Post archive previews, trim to:_ xxxxxx (text field)  words / characters (radio button)\r\n* _Post archive previews, strip HTML:_ Yes / No (radio button)\r\n\r\nThe defaults on these settings could be determined by the theme, but the helper could look to see if the user had set anything in these fields, and if so override the output with those saved settings.\r\n\r\nCould this perhaps be a relatively neat and simple way to give users some control over these display settings?\r\n\r\nI may be missing something that\'s planned for the future advanced excerpts in line for 0.8, but if not, what do you think?\r\n\r\nI\'m still something of a beginner, but looking at the current helper functions I think I\'d be up for taking a run at combining them if the idea has any merit.\r\n'
2322,'','Split Ghost into two applications?\nLet me preface by saying \r\n\r\n> Not been one of the core devs, am properly really wrong about this.\r\n\r\nI think the problems outlined by @ErisDS in #2144 stem from a conflict between two major parts of Ghost, namely Ghost the Blog part and Ghost the Admin part.\r\n\r\nThe Admin part is a modern, advanced web application. And requires appropriate tools and techniques to build it.\r\n\r\nThe Blog part in stark contrast is a quite simple website. Consisting of just two pages (the home page and post page). This is by design as using other techniques would likely lead to **unacceptable** side-effects like poor seo.\r\n\r\nI think it\'s these opposing approaches to building an application that has\r\n\r\n> resulting in confusion between what goes where, and code split between the client and the server.\r\n\r\nSo given this situation wouldn\'t it make sense to split Ghost into two applications?\r\n\r\n**Ghost**\r\nAn express app, serves the home page, the post page and api endpoints. Would have limited client-side functionality but continue to use backbone for structure.\r\n\r\n**Ghost Admin**\r\nA full-on single page application, using the ember framework. Without the constraints of living within the same repo as the Ghost Blog, Ghost Admin can simply adopt the conventions (especially directory structure) provided by a framework like ember. This way the whole "what goes where" issue, should disappear.\r\n\r\n**Ghost Apps**\r\nHaving not seen any Ghost Apps and how they are architected, am not sure how this approach would effect them. But perhaps it would help to simplify them. Ghost Apps will have to **"make-up the mind"**, they will either be a Ghost Blog App (enhance the user facing frontend in someway) or Ghost Admin App (help the blogger better manage his/her blog on the backend.)\r\n\r\n**NOTE:** When I say split Ghost into two applications, I don\'t mean to imply that the user has to go and download two apps. Ghost Admin will automatically packaged into the main app (similar to how Casper is pulled in) and would be proxied/accessible at **/admin**.\r\n'
