1986,'','bug caused by unidecode\'s bug\nI post a new article with title"第一篇". The article link will become \'http://127.0.0.1:2368/Di%20[/?]%20Pian%20/\', and 404 error happen. After some check,Ｉthink it\'s caused by module unidecode. Test code(in index.js):\r\n<pre><code>\r\nunidecode = require(\'unidecode\');\r\nconsole.log("unidecode(第一篇) = " + unidecode("第一篇") + "\\n");\r\n</code></pre>\r\nResult:\r\n<pre><code>\r\nE:\\node_js\\Ghost>npm start\r\n\r\n> ghost@0.4.0 start E:\\node_js\\Ghost\r\n> node index\r\n\r\nunidecode(第一篇) = Di [?] Pian\r\n</code></pre>\r\nIt seems unidecode cannot decode chinese word \'一" correctly.'
1985,'','ghost 0.4.0 fails under windows with an exception when "wrong" utf8 chars detected\nI have started to do some fuzzing on ghost with a local instance running on Windows 7, which hasn\'t turned up much yet, however I found one issue that is probably due to the error 400 or 500 page failing to display.\r\n\r\nI tried to reproduce the issue with Linux, there it doesn\'t show, so I guess this is a Windows only issue, which makes it a bit low priority since I assume nobody is using Windows in any kind of production hosting.\r\n\r\nWhen accessing the url http://yourhost/%c0%af, the ghost server should give a 400 or 500 error since that is an invalid utf8 char, that would decode to / and was used on some attacks to circumvent path traversal protection (I believe this was an issue in Tomcat at some point, the problem was that the security filter that checked for ../.. paths was applied before the path was decoded so that ..%c0af.. was decoded to ../.. afterwards). Apparently ghost or more likely the node.js webserver catches that quite nicely, but then fails to display the 400 page.\r\n\r\nThe same error doesn\'t happen in the 0.3.3 version and it doesn\'t seem to happen on Linux installations of Ghost (for example it doesn\'t happen on my ghost install on runkite).\r\n\r\nWhen running in production mode, the server displays a generic bad request message (but still has the exception), when running in development mode, the stack trace is shown in the error 400 page.\r\n\r\nThe exception looks like this:\r\n\r\n```\r\nError: Cannot find module \'hbs\'\r\n    at Function.Module._resolveFilename (module.js:338:15)\r\n    at Function.Module._load (module.js:280:25)\r\n    at Module.require (module.js:364:17)\r\n    at require (module.js:380:17)\r\n    at new View (C:\\Projects\\Ghost\\ghost-git\\Ghost\\node_modules\\express\\lib\\view.js:43:49)\r\n    at Function.app.render (C:\\Projects\\Ghost\\ghost-git\\Ghost\\node_modules\\express\\lib\\application.js:486:12)\r\n    at ServerResponse.res.render (C:\\Projects\\Ghost\\ghost-git\\Ghost\\node_modules\\express\\lib\\response.js:798:7)\r\n    at renderErrorInt (C:\\Projects\\Ghost\\ghost-git\\Ghost\\core\\server\\errorHandling.js:162:30)\r\n    at Object.errors.renderErrorPage (C:\\Projects\\Ghost\\ghost-git\\Ghost\\core\\server\\errorHandling.js:179:16)\r\n    at Object.errors.error500 (C:\\Projects\\Ghost\\ghost-git\\Ghost\\core\\server\\errorHandling.js:206:20)\r\nGET /%c0%af 400 72ms - 831b\r\n```\r\n\r\nI do not know of any web testing environments that actually support running node.js in Windows (Travis-ci has a lengthy thread that this would be desirable, but they have not yet implemented it), so I cannot be sure if this is caused by something specific to my machine, but I don\'t think it is.\r\n\r\n'
1984,'',"Use absolute path when storing images\ncloses #1983\r\n\r\nImages were uploaded to a relative location, based on the current directory. So if you start Ghost using `node ~/Ghost/index.js`, it would put all images at `~/content/images`.\r\n\r\nThis changes it to use a absolute directory, based on Ghost's root directory (see `server/config/paths.js`).\r\n\r\n@simme Can you please verify that it solves the problem?\r\n\r\n@ErisDS Because the bug pollutes the user's file system, you might consider pushing the fix as an update to 0.4."
