1967,'ErisDS','body_class overhaul\nWhen _page.hbs_ template is used, `body_class` list "post-template" instead of "page-template".\r\n"*-template" class name should change based on currently used `.hbs` filename.\r\nThat would be really helpful when developing themes.'
1966,'',"Bug: Memory leak detected on startup before any request is made.\n### Issue Summary\r\n\r\nGhost 0.4.0 is using considerably more memory than Ghost 0.3.3. It also appears that there is a memory leak.\r\n\r\n### Steps to Reproduce\r\n\r\nBy adding the following code between the two lines of Ghost's root index.js it is possible to do a very crude output of memory usage:\r\n\r\n```\r\nfunction recordMemory() {\r\n    console.log('MEMORY', process.memoryUsage());\r\n}\r\n \r\nsetInterval(recordMemory, 6000 * 2);\r\nrecordMemory();\r\n```\r\n\r\nAfter entering this code, run `npm start` but do not open Ghost in a browser. Just leave it to start up, run, and spit out a few values for memory usage..\r\n\r\nDoing this on Ghost 0.3.3 results in 4 RSS outputs which increase, and then it stabilizes and the RSS remains the same.\r\n\r\nOn Ghost 0.4, the RSS climbs steadily :anguished:\r\n\r\nI have done a [set of tests](https://gist.github.com/ErisDS/871d1e32b090156bd4e3) across various 0.4 commits, and narrowed this change in behaviour down to this commit (it's mine): https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/commit/af61372\r\n\r\nFurther investigations have narrowed this down to the inclusion and usage of moment.js in `config/paths.js`. I am still in the process of investigating and fixing the issue.\r\n\r\n### Technical details: \r\n\r\n* Ghost Version: af61372 onwards\r\n* Client OS: Mac OS X 10.8.5\r\n* Server OS: Localhost\r\n* Node Version: 0.10.18\r\n* Browser: Chrome 31.0.1650.63"
1965,'',"[Docs] Ghost Hosted Platform Docs\nPlease can someone check for spelling mistakes, everything else should be OK :)\r\n\r\n# Introduces\r\n\r\n* A new 'Get Started' page to choose between the Ghost hosted platform and self-hosting\r\n* A new Ghost hosted platform page"
1964,'ErisDS',"Empty partials cause error 500\nSince 0.4 there is an exception thrown on main index page:\r\n```\r\nYou must pass a string or Handlebars AST to Handlebars.compile. You passed function (context, options) { if (!compiled) { compiled = compileInput(); } return compiled.call(this, context, options); }\r\n```\r\n\r\nOccurs when one of below custom/partials is blank:\r\nhttps://github.com/oswaldoacauan/ghostium/tree/master/src/partials/custom\r\n\r\nException is thrown here:\r\n```\r\n// If the partial view is not compiled, it compiles and saves in handlebars\r\n    if (typeof partial === 'string') {\r\n        partial = hbs.handlebars.compile(partial);\r\n        hbs.handlebars.partials[name] = partial;\r\n    }\r\n```\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/blob/968176c7d70cd171f22f4f67476a46f227c1c855/core/server/helpers/template.js#L19\r\n\r\nAdding below to an empty partial fixes an issue:\r\n```\r\n{{! any comment here }}\r\n```\r\n\r\n* Ghost Version: master (latest commit: c82d2eadba0176ce96ec91d57bfa8582cae50f95)\r\n* Server OS: Archlinux, Ubuntu 13.04, OSX 10.8.5\r\n* Node Version: 0.10\r\n\r\nOriginal issue reported [here](https://github.com/oswaldoacauan/ghostium/issues/47#issuecomment-32184528)"
1963,'',"The ability to print citations without copying them twice.\nIt's become commonplace to have citations at the bottom of blog posts in the format that is used in markdown:\r\n\r\n```\r\n[1] http://sourceA/\r\n[2] http://sourceB/\r\n[3] http://sourceC/\r\n```\r\nand then perhaps link to them in the text, like this:\r\n\r\n```\r\nAs said by Rob Ford<sup>[1]<sup>, all bacon was created  equal\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis works well, but some people like to have their sources printed at the bottom as well, and having to print it again but in a div would be redundant.\r\n\r\nIs it possible that there could be a way to print them or toggle printing them? That would be neat and practical"
