1920,'',"Investigate more flexible code style checker\nHopefully appropriate as an issue.\r\n\r\nI came across this project today which I think may be useful to include in Ghost to keep code style consistent throughout the project.\r\n\r\n[ndoe-jscs](https://github.com/mdevils/node-jscs) - JavaScript Code Style checker\r\n\r\nThe project should be used alongside JSLint as it's only aim is to maintain the consistency of coding style throughout the code base.  JSLint does provide some of this functionality however there's some definitions that it lacks that jscs provides, such as:\r\n\r\n* [requiring curly braces around keywords](https://github.com/mdevils/node-jscs#requirecurlybraces)\r\n* [requiring `var` be used once when declaring](https://github.com/mdevils/node-jscs#requiremultiplevardecl)\r\n* [require aligned object values](https://github.com/mdevils/node-jscs#requirealignedobjectvalues)\r\n* [disallow trailing whitespace](https://github.com/mdevils/node-jscs#requirealignedobjectvalues)\r\n\r\nBecause Ghost is a community developed project it incorporates the coding styles of all those contributions.  This is fine, and good, however it'd also be healthy to encourage a coding standard across the code base so as to increase the overall maintainability of the project.  Should help with getting new developers up to speed as everything is similar in style, and should reduce any errors due to that same reason.\r\n\r\nAlso has a grunt plugin as well.  https://github.com/gustavohenke/grunt-jscs-checker\r\n"
