1710,'',"Provide warnings for insecure content in the editor\nWhen the admin is in secure mode (i.e. HTTPS) uris for images, scripts, iframes which are not HTTP will cause insecure content warnings, e.g in chrome you get this in the console:\r\n\r\n> The page at 'https://my-ghost-blog.com/ghost/editor/66/' was loaded over HTTPS, but displayed insecure content from 'http://someurl.com/someimage.png': this content should also be loaded over HTTPS.\r\n\r\nAnd this in the url bar:\r\n\r\n![](http://puu.sh/b4pPr.png)\r\n\r\nMaking it look like the site is insecure, however it is only the user-provided content causing this. \r\n\r\nA further problem is that Ghost can be setup so that the frontend of the blog is also served over HTTPS (and this is a growing trend), in which case these browser warnings would be persisted to the frontend and shown to all of the blog's readers.\r\n\r\nIn the former case, where the warning only appears to the author, the problem is pretty minor. However, I think in the latter case, there is more of a reason for us to take responsibility to help authors not include insecure content in their blog content.\r\n\r\nThe suggested solution was to highlight insecure urls in the editor in some way to indicate to the author that the uri is insecure. The idea was to apply an orange (for warning) background or border to the resource in question in the editor or preview, and to provide an explanation when the user hovered over it, or to have an icon appear that could be interacted with in some other way to get more information."
