1638,'','Ghost is running with root privileges when started with sudo command.\nSummary\r\n=======\r\n\r\nWhen you run ghost app using sudo, the app has root privileges. We should avoid this as running any public app with root privileges is always a bad idea. We do need to run it using "sudo" because we can\'t run a nodejs app on port < 1024. With this issue I will also be submitting a fix in a pull request. \r\n\r\nSteps to test\r\n==========\r\n1) When ghost creates folders inside content/images they have ownership set to "root".\r\n2) Use child_process nodejs module to run "whoami". It will show that you are "root".\r\nCode for testing with whoami:\r\n```\r\nvar whoami = require(\'child_process\').spawn(\'whoami\');\r\nvar whoami_resp = "";\r\nvar whoami_error = \'\';\r\n\r\nwhoami.stdout.on(\'data\', function (buffer) { \r\n    whoami_resp += buffer.toString(); \r\n});\r\nwhoami.stderr.on(\'data\', function (buffer) { \r\n    whoami_error += buffer.toString(); \r\n});\r\nwhoami.on(\'close\', function(code) { \r\n    console.log(\'whoami\', {\r\n        stdout: whoami_resp,\r\n        stderr: whoami_error,\r\n        exit_code: code\r\n    });\r\n}); \r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n'
1637,'','Restoring a ghost blog causes funkiness with the notifications\nWhen you export from a pre-existing Ghost instance and then import into a fresh install some interesting things happen:\r\n\r\n- Ghost overwrites your new user account with the old user account (debatable if this is expected behavior or not).\r\n- Since your old account is restored, you are logged out of your current account. This in itself isn\'t bad, but the notification stating "Data imported. Log in with the user details you imported" isn\'t displayed until **after** you log in with the old credentials :crying_cat_face:.'
