1500,'',"expand the sass task to compile theme sass files.\nTo help promote theme development, I thought it might be good for the gruntfile to compile sass files found in the theme directories.\r\n\r\nIt's just an idea, but this works for me.\r\n\r\nIt's assumed that your themes look like: \r\n\r\n```\r\ncontent/\r\n  ...\r\n  themes/\r\n    a-theme/\r\n      src/\r\n        sass/\r\n           _colours.sass\r\n           _mixins.sass\r\n           screen.sass\r\n           print.sass\r\n           ie.sass\r\n```\r\n\r\nAnd the result is : \r\n```\r\ncontent/\r\n  ...\r\n  themes/\r\n    a-theme/\r\n      assets/\r\n        css/\r\n           screen.css\r\n           print.css\r\n           ie.css\r\n      src/\r\n        sass/\r\n           _colours.sass\r\n           _mixins.sass\r\n           screen.sass\r\n           print.sass\r\n           ie.sass\r\n```"
1499,'',"Signup > Signin UX\n### The Problem\r\n\r\nWe are getting many reports of users unable to sign in to Ghost after signing up #1469.\r\n\r\nI believe this is caused, in part, by the disjoint between signing up and signing in - a users signs up, and is automatically signed in, and may not need to use their sign in details for some time - thus never knowing if they mistyped something and otherwise having lots of time to forget what they did.\r\n\r\nOriginally, Ghost forced you to sign in straight after signing up, so you had to use your details again - this way you pretty much knew straight away if you had typo'd.\r\n\r\nFrom the perspective of ease of use, it is much better UX to sign the user in automatically after sign up. However this is a one-time event, and forcing users to enter their credentials may be a better way to catch issues with typos in email addresses and passwords.\r\n\r\n### Potential changes \r\n\r\nThe common way of mitigating this is to duplicate the important email and password fields. This is a bit clunky, but again, we're talking about a one-time thing. Potentially, this is more likely to create a barrier / put people off, than asking them to sign in after they have signed up.\r\n\r\nAnother option could be to provide additional UI after signup - showing a dialog which displays the user's email and allows them to check and confirm their password if they want to or otherwise strongly messaging the user to double check their typing. Not sure if this is done in many places.\r\n\r\nYet another method would be to message more strongly if email is not available at this point to try to encourage users to configure email, and then send a welcome email (not including the password)... this is a bit rubbish though because if the user gets their email wrong they don't get the email and the lack of email is unlikely to work as a useful indicator of someone spelling their email address incorrectly.\r\n\r\nAll of this is a one-time event for each user that they have to go through. Making it easy by not having duplicate fields and not requiring both sign up and sign in is probably more helpful for developers who have to go through this process more frequently, than it is for the end user who does it once, gets it wrong, and then gets utterly confused.\r\n\r\n### Summary\r\n\r\nThis issue is here to consider the best option. In my opinion the best option is to not automagically sign users in - the 2 steps force users to consider if they did it wrong straight away, rather than coming back and assuming they've been 'locked out'. I also think it's better than duplicating the fields up front... but I've nothing to back this up."
