1385,'','Travis doesn\'t actually test MySQL\nTravis runs once with `DB=sqlite3` and once with `DB=mysql`, but both are actually running against SQLite.\r\n\r\nI noticed that `.travis.yml` [creates the `ghost_travis` database](https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/blob/master/.travis.yml#L17), while the `travis-mysql` environment [tells it to use the `ghost-travis` database](https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/blob/master/config.example.js#L109). This should cause all MySQL Travis builds to fail, yet they succeed.\r\n\r\nI then annotated `Gruntfile.js` and `core/server/models/base.js`. When run in a faux-Travis environment, I get:\r\n\r\n    $ TRAVIS=1 DB=mysql grunt validate\r\n    ...\r\n    Running "setTestEnv" task\r\n    set NODE_ENV travis-mysql\r\n\r\n    Running "loadConfig" task\r\n\r\n    Running "express:test" (express) task\r\n    Starting background Express server\r\n    using database client sqlite3 for NODE_ENV testing\r\n\r\nI tracked this down to the Express configuration which [overrides `NODE_ENV`](https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/blob/master/Gruntfile.js#L118). As a result, Express always runs in `testing` environment, and thus always runs against SQLite on Travis.'
