1279,'',"<code>/<tt> elements should wrap since they're used inline\nThis pull request changes the `code, tt` rule `white-space: pre` to `pre-wrap`. [Definitions](http://www.w3.org/TR/CSS21/text.html#white-space-prop):\r\n\r\n> **pre**\r\n> This value prevents user agents from collapsing sequences of white space. Lines are only broken at preserved newline characters.\r\n> **pre-wrap**\r\n> This value prevents user agents from collapsing sequences of white space. Lines are broken at preserved newline characters, and as necessary to fill line boxes.\r\n\r\nBefore:\r\n![white-space: pre](https://f.cloud.github.com/assets/118362/1408117/50fabd94-3d7c-11e3-9821-10a956fb83c6.png)\r\n\r\nAfter:\r\n![white-space: pre-wrap](https://f.cloud.github.com/assets/118362/1408118/562280f4-3d7c-11e3-84c3-c162074c37a5.png)\r\n\r\nSee also TryGhost/Casper#48."
1278,'','Docs: Back button to index page broken\nThe back button isn\'t working (404) when the previous page is `index`. Reproduceable [here](http://docs.ghost.org/installation/mac/) or [here](http://docs.ghost.org/usage/configuration/).\r\n\r\nThe problem lies in the `pagination.html`:\r\n```\r\n<a href="{{ site.url }}/{{page.chapter}}/{{ page.prev_section }}/"\r\n```\r\nThe link to most of the sections is `chapter_name/section_name/` (file is at `chapter_name/section_name/index.html`), BUT for the index page it is just `chapter_name/`(file is at `chapter_name/index.html`).'
1277,'',"Some 301 redirects use relative paths but probably should not\nThe 301 redirect that adds a trailing slash to all requested paths appears to use a relative path in the 'Location' header rather than an absolute path. There are 2 problems with this approach:\r\n\r\n1) RFC2616 states that the 'Location' header must contain a full URI. While many browsers will handle this situation, it is not correct, and they can be confused (see point 2).\r\n\r\n2) If you visit a path with 2 leading slashes eg: http://charlie.ghost.io//google.com you will be redirected to google.com because the browser treats the redirect URL as absolute. This could potentially be used for evil."
