928,'javorszky',"WP Export Plugin: path issue\nFrom [the forum](https://en.ghost.org/forum/using-ghost/165-importing-posts)\r\n\r\n> Unfortunately it looks like there’s a couple of problems with both the ghost plugin and the importer.\r\n\r\n> The plugin seems to assume a path and fails without error unless I explicitly set it to that of the plugin. It then downloads a file which has no content. I’ve modified the ghost-class.php so it works for me as follows:\r\n\r\n> https://gist.github.com/iwootten/6700474\r\n\r\n@javorszky hope you don't mind me punting this at you :)"
927,'',"Grunt deploy\nCreate a deploy task which:\r\n\r\n1. Packages up a zip file from the current directory for deployment, rather than for build.\r\nThis means that config.js should be included, along with any custom themes, plugins and uploaded images, but probably no databases.\r\n\r\n2. Accepts options such as an ip/hostname, username, path to key (default to not required) and remote path (default to ~/var/www/). If these options are provided, then the newly created zip file is scp'd to that server.\r\n\r\n3. Takes an `init` argument to tell it this is an initial deploy. If `init` is not specified, it's assumed that this is an upgrade. Task then ssh's into the server extracts the zip (unzip -uo should not overwrite any key files) and runs npm install.\r\n\r\n4. Finally, after logging out of ssh, the task prints out whether it has a) just created a zip or b) also deployed that zip and if it has deployed, it warns the user that they have to restart the server. It would be super handy if it outputted the appropriate ssh command ready to ssh to the server.\r\n\r\nOoorrrr... maybe someone smart can think of something better for step 4 that gets us closer to a full deploy inc restart."
