553,'',"Restoring form-data on editor panel\nDid you ever type out a big long post in the Ghost editor, accidentally hit a link, back button or close the tab, and then get it back to find you've lost everything? \r\n\r\nDid you ever type out a big long comment/issue on Github, accidentally hit a link, back button or close the tab, and then get it back to find your comment/issue still waiting to be submitted?\r\n\r\nI believe that this is a browser behaviour which depends on certain things. Something about the way that CodeMirror works doesn't work with the behaviour. That or there is some fancy thing on github that we should emulate.\r\n\r\nAt the very least, I'd like someone to investigate why Ghost's editor doesn't exhibit this behaviour, and Github does, and what the requirements are for fixing it.\r\n"
552,'',"Post titles, slugs and auto-save\nThis issue is intended as a place for discussion for now.\r\n\r\nWe want to introduce auto-saving on posts. This is reasonably easy to do.. ish..  but has some caveats around post title & slug that we need to work out.\r\n\r\nThe rules at the moment:\r\n\r\n* Post title cannot be blank when saving a post.\r\n* This is because we need the title to generate the slug.\r\n* Once a slug has been generated, it should not be updated except manually (coming in #370)\r\n* This is because changing the permalink without the user knowing is bad - they won't know the URL for their post has changed.\r\n\r\nSo there are problems to deal with - how do we auto-save without a title? Do we just throw a notification to the user saying we can't? Do we save a dummy title/slug?\r\n\r\nWhat about if we auto-save halfway through the user authoring their title? They'll get half a slug...\r\n\r\nShould we relax the rules, and updating a slug up until the post is published, rather than never? What about if a post is unpublished and re-published?\r\n"
