4373,'',"[WIP] No more CodeMirror\n:boom: :fireworks: :boom: :tada: :boom:\r\n\r\nThis PR needs SIGNIFICANT cross browser and device testing - here's how to [test a PR](http://dev.ghost.org/easy-git-pr-test/)\r\n\r\nIt represents a complete reimplementation of the existing functionality we had with codemirror with a few exceptions:\r\n- the new, simpler image upload code no longer uses markers to map between the left and right panes, and instead does a quick lookup, which should work equally well on all devices\r\n- it may be necessary to change the image upload code to make sure that the event which re-enables the textarea is fired after the processing is complete, rather than after the image upload is complete (this is a maybe TODO)\r\n- now that we don't have awkward markers to keep track of, the image upload regex can be updated in both the `ghostimagepreview.js` and `image-manager.js` to be a much more powerful regex which properly supports [image titles](https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/issues/985) (this is a TODO)\r\n- the shortcodes have been reimplemented to be slightly smarter about where the cursor goes after, and whether or not they require a newline (more to be done here to make the list shortcut better) \r\n- the textarea does not capture TAB. This can be added, but I'm not 100% whether it's a blessing or a curse - so lets do some testing without before adding it (this is a maybe TODO)\r\n\r\n**Note**  I've not looked at linting or tests yet\r\n\r\n- [x] Finish up link and image shortcuts\r\n- [x] Get the editor scrolling as you type\r\n- [ ] Improve the image regex\r\n- [ ] Maybe add TAB handling\r\n- [ ] Maybe change image upload events\r\n- [x] Fix existing tests\r\n- [ ] Add new tests\r\n\r\ncloses #4368, fixes #1240 (spellcheck) and more\r\n\r\n- Drop CodeMirror in favour of a plain text area\r\n- Use rangyinputs to handle selections cross-browser\r\n- Create an API for interacting with the textarea\r\n- Replace marker manager with a much simpler image manager\r\n- Reimplement shortcuts, including some bug fixes\r\n- Rename components include editor-route-base"
4368,'ErisDS',"Drop CodeMirror from the Editor\nWith reference to the [Split Screen Editor Epic (#1294)](https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/issues/1294)\r\n\r\n--- \r\n\r\nThe Ghost editor undeniably needs some :heart:. No matter how you consider what the editor might look like in the future, there is one underlying problem - to ship improvements like spellcheck, we need to build a completely custom editor, that's an enormous undertaking, and it would detract from all the other features we want to ship :-1:.\r\n\r\nThat is, unless we drop formatting/syntax highlighting from the left side of the editor :boom: \r\n\r\n**yep**... I'm talking about dropping CodeMirror in favour of a plain textarea.\r\n\r\nCodeMirror currently has two main jobs: 1) it formats/syntax highlights the markdown and 2) provides an API for interacting with the entered text. However, what it does under the bonnet is generate a completely custom representation of the document which is neither markdown or HTML. This breaks the [browser spellcheck](https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/issues/1240), doesn't work reliably [on mobile/touch](https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/issues/960) (which meant we had to remove it from mobile/touch devices), and the way it interprets markdown is quite different to our HTML conversion, which causes [weird](https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/issues/959) [bugs](https://github.com/TryGhost/Ghost/issues/1909) and adds complexity.\r\n\r\nIf we strip out CodeMirror, we will lose formatting, but what we get instead will be an editor with working **spellcheck**, working **mobile uploads** and significantly reduced complexity: because we only have two document representations - markdown and HTML, and we are in control of them both. This means we can focus on making the conversion between them better (i.e. adding advanced markdown features).\r\n\r\nIn the future, we'll be able to bring back formatting if we want it using contenteditable, but in the meantime we can more easily focus on the features we want to bring to the editor, the markdown we want to support, and creating our own way of modelling documents - because the editor is so significantly less complicated.\r\n\r\nI've been working on a prototype testing out how to interact with selections in the textarea to make sure that image uploads will still work (on ALL devices) etc and to me this feels like taking back control, and I'm REALLY, _**ridiculously**_ excited about it."
4366,'',"Post Settings Meta fields too long errors don't go away\nIf you run into the top limits on the meta title and description fields (150 and 200), fix the problem and try to save again, the error message still shows.\r\n\r\n([original report](https://ghost.org/forum/bugs-suggestions/16907-old-meta-data-won-t-clear-after-error/))\r\n\r\n### Steps to Reproduce\r\n\r\n1. Create a new post \r\n2. Fill out meta_description to more than 200 chars\r\n3. Close PSM & Save\r\n4. Reopen PSM, fix meta description to < 200 chars\r\n5. Close PSM save\r\n5. See there's still an error, but it did actually save, I think...\r\n\r\n### Technical details: \r\n\r\n* Ghost Version: master & 0.5.3"
4364,'',"Auto-indent of partials causes problems with rendering code blocks in blog posts\nThere is an ongoing discussion about this on the [handlebars repo](https://github.com/wycats/handlebars.js/issues/858#issuecomment-61109359). It was originally discovered as a sort-of-bug-in-Ghost via a weird issue [on the forum](https://ghost.org/forum/using-ghost/16929-indentations-syntax-highlightling/) and applies to [themes which use a partial to output content](https://github.com/haydenbleasel/ghost-themes/blob/phantom/post.hbs#L15). I'm raising it here as a way to keep track of it.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nEssentially, in Handlebars 2.0.0, any partial which is indented is now rendered with that indent applied to the beginning of every line output by the partial. So if I have a partial like:\r\n\r\n```\r\n<section>\r\n{{content}}\r\n</section>\r\n```\r\n\r\nand I output it in my `post.hbs` like:\r\n\r\n```\r\n<body>\r\n    {{> my-partial}}\r\n</body>\r\n```\r\n\r\nThen every line of the partial, including every line output by `{{content}}` will have 4 spaces applied at the beginning, just like the `    {{> my-partial}}` line has.\r\n\r\nThis sort of makes sense - it makes for nicely aligned source code, but it also fudges with anything in the partial which is whitespace-sensitive, like a `<pre>` or a `<textarea>`. Essentially, if you have a nicely formatted code block in your blog content, when it gets rendered to the page, all the lines of code will weirdly have 4 extra spaces at the start.\r\n\r\nThe solution is simple enough - don't use a partial, or don't indent your partial, but this behaviour is very hard to predict in my opinion.\r\n\r\nThe discussion on the [handlebars repo](https://github.com/wycats/handlebars.js/issues/858#issuecomment-61109359) might lead to a compiler flag we can use to disable this. Alternatively we could downgrade back to handlebars 1.3.0 for rendering themes. If we do neither of these, then we have to be very careful to document this behaviour."
4362,'',"Encode helper is broken in many fabulous ways\nHey,\r\n\r\nJust working on [an issue](https://github.com/haydenbleasel/ghost-themes/issues/13) for one of my themes where I can't use the `{{encode}}` helper on the homepage. Basically I've made the sharing links (Twitter, Facebook, etc - similar to the one in Casper) a partial so it can be included on any page, but `{{encode title}}` or `{{encode meta_title}}` both return `%5Bobject%20Object%5D` on the homepage. Looked through the Ghost docs and there wasn't any sign of a post-template only restriction so I'm opening it up as a bug here."
